00:31:49,657 --> 00:31:54,412
But you have a perspective on math,
and that is quite unique.

384
00:31:56,873 --> 00:31:58,249
I like it.

385
00:32:24,943 --> 00:32:25,860
MATH CLASSROOM

386
00:33:38,766 --> 00:33:40,101
How about trying this?

387
00:33:40,685 --> 00:33:41,894
Since when…

388
00:36:12,753 --> 00:36:14,797
MATH CLASSROOM

389
00:36:42,366 --> 00:36:45,494
You'll keep working
on this problem, right?

390
00:36:46,245 --> 00:36:47,747
Well, I haven't found the solution yet.

391
00:36:55,129 --> 00:36:57,340
Promise me one thing.

392
00:37:08,309 --> 00:37:10,645
Don't fall in love with this problem.

393
00:37:12,521 --> 00:37:17,318
As a mathematician,
solving a problem doesn't make you happy.

394
00:37:18,110 --> 00:37:20,696
Also, an unsolvable problem
doesn't make you unhappy too.

395
00:37:23,366 --> 00:37:25,201
Then why do mathematicians

396
00:37:26,619 --> 00:37:28,496
keep solving problems?

397
00:37:28,579 --> 00:37:30,206
When you work on it,

398
00:37:30,915 --> 00:37:32,250
there's a tingling sensation,

399
00:37:33,167 --> 00:37:34,293
excitement,

400
00:37:35,544 --> 00:37:36,754
or anxiety that you feel.

401
00:37:44,011 --> 00:37:46,013
Whether or not you find the answer,

402
00:37:46,681 --> 00:37:48,599
it's the moment
when you're engrossed in it

403
00:37:49,725 --> 00:37:52,061
that enraptures you.

404
00:38:05,866 --> 00:38:07,243
We stayed up all night.

405
00:38:07,994 --> 00:38:09,537
I came to erase the problem.

406
00:38:10,913 --> 00:38:11,747
Why?

407
00:38:17,545 --> 00:38:19,672
I felt like I was imposing it on you.

408
00:38:22,550 --> 00:38:25,928
I'd like you to be free
from any constraints.

409
00:38:37,189 --> 00:38:38,274
Here.

410
00:38:39,108 --> 00:38:40,484
I found your button.

411
00:38:41,235 --> 00:38:42,153
What?

412
00:38:44,363 --> 00:38:45,573
You found it.

413
00:38:50,036 --> 00:38:51,078
Thanks.

414
00:38:59,670 --> 00:39:01,088
What did you say?

415
00:39:07,053 --> 00:39:08,429
Ms. Ji spent the night…

416
00:39:10,264 --> 00:39:12,516
with that student.

417
00:39:14,435 --> 00:39:17,063
The student you told me to look into.

418
00:39:17,146 --> 00:39:19,106
Paik Seung-yoo. 11th Grade, Class No. 8.

419
00:39:20,066 --> 00:39:23,486
Bring me Paik Seung-yoo's files.

420
00:39:24,945 --> 00:39:26,030
Okay, Director.

421
00:39:37,958 --> 00:39:41,212
So that's the end of detention.

422
00:39:42,505 --> 00:39:44,382
You don't need to come tomorrow.

423
00:40:04,693 --> 00:40:06,028
That was exhilarating.

424
00:40:11,325 --> 00:40:13,494
But I'm also afraid.

425
00:40:15,246 --> 00:40:19,166
You're Paik Seung-yoo,
not Paik Min-jae anymore.

426
00:40:20,543 --> 00:40:22,169
I'm glad to meet you.

427
00:40:55,786 --> 00:40:57,204
WINNER: GOLDEN MORNING STAR

428
00:41:01,584 --> 00:41:02,418
All right!

429
00:41:03,669 --> 00:41:06,297
Hey, did you see that?

430
00:41:06,380 --> 00:41:08,507
I told you that Golden Morning Star
would win.

431
00:41:08,591 --> 00:41:10,468
I'm a good judge of horses.

432
00:41:10,551 --> 00:41:13,304
The horse I picked could have won.
It came in second.

433
00:41:13,929 --> 00:41:15,473
-The Number Three horse?
-Yes.

434
00:41:16,724 --> 00:41:18,476
No, it didn't have a chance.

435
00:41:18,559 --> 00:41:21,520
It was never in the lead even once.

436
00:41:21,604 --> 00:41:24,690
So that's not winning. It just lost.

437
00:41:26,108 --> 00:41:27,109
Now listen.

438
00:41:27,651 --> 00:41:31,280
A winning horse is usually sired
by a champion horse.

439
00:41:31,363 --> 00:41:32,615
Their stature is different.

440
00:41:32,698 --> 00:41:34,492
They have got broad shoulders,

441
00:41:34,575 --> 00:41:37,578
a thick chest and a slender hind profile.

442
00:41:38,787 --> 00:41:41,624
They have to be born with good genes?

443
00:41:43,959 --> 00:41:46,045
So if they're not born with those traits,

444
00:41:46,128 --> 00:41:49,298
they can't win
no matter how hard they try?

445
00:41:50,966 --> 00:41:52,384
What?

446
00:41:52,468 --> 00:41:55,054
They already have
a head start when they're born.

447
00:41:55,137 --> 00:41:57,598
So there's no way you can beat them.

448
00:41:59,141 --> 00:42:00,434
Isn't that true?

449
00:42:07,900 --> 00:42:08,901
Hi.

450
00:42:09,735 --> 00:42:10,861
Have a seat.

451
00:42:16,659 --> 00:42:18,035
Why did you call me at this hour?

452
00:42:21,747 --> 00:42:23,249
You're busy
since the semester began, right?

453
00:42:23,332 --> 00:42:25,084
Book a spa when you have time.

454
00:42:26,001 --> 00:42:29,129
Are the school math contest
preparations coming along fine?

455
00:42:29,964 --> 00:42:32,841
There's not much to do.
We always administer tests.

456
00:42:32,925 --> 00:42:36,470
But must you let
all your students enter the math contest?

457
00:42:38,931 --> 00:42:40,849
-What's the matter?
-It's a lot of work.

458
00:42:40,933 --> 00:42:42,309
You have to grade them.

459
00:42:43,227 --> 00:42:45,354
And there is no need
to give false hope either.

460
00:42:45,437 --> 00:42:46,647
False hope?

461
00:42:46,730 --> 00:42:50,859
I'm not saying this will happen,
but what if some random kid gets chosen,

462
00:42:50,943 --> 00:42:53,654
-but has to relinquish his entry ticket?
-A random kid?

463
00:42:54,780 --> 00:42:56,949
-You mean Paik Seung-yoo?
-You know that kid?

464
00:42:57,533 --> 00:43:00,911
Senator, he's not a kid.
He goes to our school.

465
00:43:00,995 --> 00:43:02,246
That kid is…

466
00:43:05,207 --> 00:43:07,084
I know that kid.

467
00:43:07,710 --> 00:43:09,795
He's got lots of problems.

468
00:43:09,878 --> 00:43:13,090
He was called a math genius,
but that turned out to be all hype.

469
00:43:13,799 --> 00:43:16,343
You know he's the worst student
in your school.

470
00:43:16,427 --> 00:43:19,013
Then what's there to worry about him?

471
00:43:19,096 --> 00:43:20,472
I'm not worried.

472
00:43:21,181 --> 00:43:23,058
I just want to avoid a messy situation.

473
00:43:23,142 --> 00:43:24,810
We've planned this
whole Olympics project together.

474
00:43:24,893 --> 00:43:26,562
Planning it…

475
00:43:27,896 --> 00:43:29,732
doesn't mean we pick the winners.

476
00:43:29,815 --> 00:43:31,358
What are you saying?

477
00:43:32,151 --> 00:43:33,277
What about Ye-lin then?

478
00:43:34,820 --> 00:43:36,614
Senator, why are you acting like this?

479
00:43:37,197 --> 00:43:39,575
-Like a demanding child.
-What?

480
00:43:40,743 --> 00:43:41,744
A child?

481
00:43:44,121 --> 00:43:48,042
Do you know how to get
what you want the easy way?

482
00:43:50,044 --> 00:43:51,920
Instead of saying what you want,

483
00:43:52,630 --> 00:43:55,716
you listen to what the other person wants.

484
00:44:00,596 --> 00:44:02,473
-Did you like the food?
-It was delicious.

485
00:44:04,058 --> 00:44:06,769
When will they start the next show?

486
00:44:08,937 --> 00:44:11,315
Oh, my, Ms. Noh.

487
00:44:13,859 --> 00:44:14,860
Oh, hello, Ms. Yoo.

488
00:44:15,444 --> 00:44:16,779
What brings you here?

489
00:44:16,862 --> 00:44:18,989
I'm having dinner
with our TV production crew.

490
00:44:19,073 --> 00:44:20,491
I had a meeting here.

491
00:44:20,574 --> 00:44:23,577
I see. But why are you alone?

492
00:44:24,286 --> 00:44:26,580
Something came up, so I need to go.

493
00:44:26,664 --> 00:44:27,706
Really?

494
00:44:28,707 --> 00:44:31,710
I should be treating you to a nice dinner.

495
00:44:31,794 --> 00:44:33,921
-Let's go out together.
-Shall we? Okay.

496
00:44:34,004 --> 00:44:35,047
Let's go.

497
00:44:38,258 --> 00:44:39,385
Goodbye.

498
00:44:48,143 --> 00:44:50,229
I'll treat you to a nice dinner soon.

499
00:44:50,312 --> 00:44:51,939
-Oh, sure.
-Good night.

500
00:44:52,523 --> 00:44:54,191
-Take care.
-Okay.

